The ISI at `PC=LR=0x000E2B04` plus NDS/GBA getting stuck on white/black screens while FPS still ticks points at **wrong control flow in the JIT**, not a dead scheduler. Two bugs in the condition machinery invert or scramble almost every conditional branch/data-processing op; a few related holes make that fatal on GBA (Emerald).

## Root causes

### 1. `mtcrf` flag mapping does not match `condPpc` (critical)

ARM CPSR bits are `N=31 Z=30 C=29 V=28`.  
`mtcrf 0x01, RCPSR` copies **bits 28–31** into CR7 as:

| CR7 bit | BI | Actual flag |
|---------|----|-------------|
| LT      | 28 | **V**       |
| GT      | 29 | **C**       |
| EQ      | 30 | **Z**       |
| SO      | 31 | **N**       |

Your `condPpc` assumed the opposite packing (LT=N, GT=Z, …), so EQ tested C, MI tested V, etc.

### 2. `emitCondSkip` polarity is inverted (critical)

```cpp
// WRONG: uses inverted BO
uint8_t inv=(cb.bo==12)?4u:12u;
ctx.E(ppc_bc(inv,cb.bi,8));
ctx.E(ppc_b(0));  // skip body
// body
```

With `bc(inv)` then `b after`:
- condition **true** → fall into `b after` → **skip body**
- condition **false** → branch to body → **run body**

So every conditional was backwards. Together with (1), BIOS/boot code mis-branches → logo then black/white screen, FPS still advancing via `JitHelp_tick` / `endFrame`.

Thumb conditional branches used the same inverted pattern.

### 3. Secondary holes that bite Emerald

- `emitMul` ignored the condition field (muls always ran).
- `rm==15` / `rs==15` indexed `RA[15]` (only 0..14 exist) → OOB read, garbage op2, bad BX targets.
- HI/LS/GE/LT/GT/LE always fell back (ok but slow); better to emit CR ops.
- Allowing the code buffer in **MEM2** is unsafe on Wii unless you set an IBAT — execute from MEM2 → ISI. Prefer MEM1 only.

